{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Cassia Cathleen Spohn | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Criminology]], [[criminal justice]] | workplaces = [[Arizona State University]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater =[[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]] | thesis_title = The role of advisory boards in the national policy-making process | thesis_url = http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/dissertations/AAI7900357/ | thesis_year = 1978 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Research on [[rape law]] | influences = | influenced = | awards = 2013 Faculty Achievement Award for Defining Edge Research in Social Sciences from Arizona State University | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''Cassia Cathleen Spohn''' is a Foundation professor at [[Arizona State University]], where she is also the director of the School of Criminology and Criminal Justice. ==Education== Spohn attended the [[University of Nebraska-Lincoln]], where she received her B.A. in journalism and political science in 1973, and her M.A. and Ph.D. in political science in 1975 and 1978, respectively.<ref name=cv>{{cite web | url=https://live-crim.ws.asu.edu/sites/default/files/%5Bterm%3Aname%5D/%5Bnode%3Acreate%3Acustom%3AYm%5D/cassia-spohn-2.pdf | title=Cassia Spohn CV | accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> ==Career== Spohn joined the faculty of the [[University of Nebraska at Omaha]] in 1978 as an assistant professor in the Goodrich Scholarship Program. In 1987, she was appointed a professor in the Department of Criminal Justice there, a position she held until joining Arizona State University in 2006. From 2005 to 2006, she served as the chair of the Department of Criminal Justice at the University of Nebraska at Omaha.<ref name=cv/> In 2011, she became a Foundation professor at Arizona State University.<ref name=ccj>{{cite web | url=https://ccj.asu.edu/content/cassia-spohn-0 | title=Cassia Spohn | work=Arizona State University | accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref> ==Research== Spohn has published over 100 papers on various subjects in the field of criminal justice, including the effects of race and sex on federal sentencing decisions, the deterrent effect of prison, and the processing of sexual assault cases.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2014/02/10/us-commanders-in-japan-overruled-court-martial-recommendation-in-2-rape-cases.html | title=US commanders in Japan overruled court-martial recommendation in 2 rape cases, dropped charges, analysis shows | work=Fox News | date=10 February 2014 | accessdate=2 May 2016 | author=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/02/02/what-makes-the-rape-case-against-bill-cosby-so-unusual/ | title=What makes the rape case against Bill Cosby so unusual | work=Washington Post | date=2 February 2016 | accessdate=2 May 2016 | author=Ehrenfreund, Max}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/to-catch-a-rapist.html?_r=0 | title=To Catch a Rapist | work=New York Times Magazine | date=10 January 2016 | accessdate=2 May 2016 | author=Dobie, Kathy}}</ref> In 1987, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] cited her research in the landmark [[capital punishment]] case [[McCleskey v. Kemp]].<ref name=ccj/>
==Honors and awards== In 1985, Spohn became a Graduate College Faculty Fellow at the University of Nebraska.<ref name=cv/> In 2013, she received the Faculty Achievement Award for Defining Edge Research in Social Sciences from Arizona State University.<ref name=ccj/> ==Editorial activities== Since 2011, Spohn has been the [[editor-in-chief]] of ''[[Justice Quarterly]]''.<ref name=ccj/> ==References== {{Reflist}} ==External links== *{{Google Scholar id|poexa3wAAAAJ}} {{Authority control}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Spohn, Cassia Cathleen}}
