[[File:Grace 3576203928 0354dda229 o.jpg|thumb|300px]] '''Daisy Grace''' in 1912 was accused of drugging her husband, Eugene H. Grace and then shooting him for his insurance money in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Legal Fight Begins for Policies on the Life of Rich Georgian Strangely Shot. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1912/03/09/archives/grace-dying-sues-wife-he-accuses-legal-fight-begins-for-policies-on.html |quote=Daisy Grace drugged her husband and then shot him. Her action was the execution of a diabolical plot to murder Eugene H. Grace for his insurance money, which the woman planned several days before. She says she drugged him before she shot him, and the evidence so far uncovered proves it. ... |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 9, 1912 |accessdate=2009-11-27 }}</ref> She was tried and found not guilty.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. Daisy Grace Found Not Guilty |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/763351612.html?dids=763351612:763351612&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+03%2C+1912&author=&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=MRS.+DAISY+GRACE+FOUND+NOT+GUILTY&pqatl=google |work=[[The Hartford Courant]] |date=August 2, 1912 |page=1 |quote=Mrs. Daisy Ople Grace was declared not guilty of trying to kill her husband by a jury here at 6 o'clock this evening.}}</ref>
