[[File:Ethnicities_and_religions_in_Iran.png|thumb|300px|Right|Ethnicities and religions in Iran]]
A majority of the [[demographics of Iran|population of Iran]] (approximately 67–80%) consists of [[Iranic peoples]].<ref name="LibraryOfCongress">"Iran" in ''Encyclopedia of Islam'', Leiden. C.E. Bosworth (editor): 
Persians (65 percent), Azeri Turks (16 percent), Kurds (7 percent), Lurs (6 percent), Arabs (2 percent), Baluchis (2 percent), Turkmens (1 percent), Turkish tribal groups such as the Qashqai (1 percent), and non-Persian, non-Turkic groups such as Armenians, Assyrians, and Georgians (less than 1 percent). {{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Iran.pdf |title=Ethnic Groups and Languages of Iran |first=Library of Congress – Federal Research Division |last=Library of Congress|accessdate=2009-12-02}}</ref><ref name="worldfactbook">According to the [[CIA World Factbook]], the ethnic breakdown of Iran is as follows: Persian 61%, Azeri 16%, Kurd 10%, Lur 6%, Baloch 2%, Arab 2%, Turkmen and Turkic tribes 2%, other 1%. {{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |title=The World Factbook – Iran |accessdate=2008-04-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203093100/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |archivedate=3 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name="Ali Gheissari">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KTou9VwtQfkC |title=Contemporary Iran : Economy, Society, Politics: Economy, Society, Politics - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2009-03-05 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref name="Ali Aldosari">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j894miuOqc4C |title=World and Its Peoples - Marshall Cavendish |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2006-09-01 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>
The largest groups in this category include [[Persian people|Persians]] (who form the majority of the Iranian population) and [[Kurdish people|Kurds]], with smaller communities including [[Gilaki people|Gilakis]], [[Mazandarani people|Mazandaranis]], [[Lurs]], [[Tat people (Iran)|Tats]], [[Talysh people|Talysh]], and [[Baloch people|Baloch]].

[[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] groups constitute a substantial minority of about 15–24%, the largest group being the [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijani]], who are the second largest ethnicity in Iran as well as the largest minority group.<ref name="books.google.nl">Brenda Shaffer. [https://books.google.com/books?id=uEOd-cDWVwQC&pg=PA229 ''The Limits of Culture: Islam and Foreign Policy''] MIT Press, 2006 {{ISBN|0262195291}} p 229</ref> Other Turkic groups include the [[Turkmen people|Turkmen]] and [[Qashqai people|Qashqai]] peoples.

[[Arabs of Khuzestan|Arabs]] account for about 2&ndash;3% of the Iranian population.
The remainder, amounting to about 1% of Iranian population, consists of a variety of minor groups, mainly comprising [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]], [[Armenian people|Armenians]], [[Iranian Georgians|Georgians]], [[Circassians]],<ref name="Carl Waldman pp.175">Carl Waldman, Catherine Mason, ''Encyclopedia of European Peoples'', pp.175</ref> and
[[Mandaeans]].<ref name="saving">{{cite web|author=Russell Contrera |url=http://www.hollandsentinel.com/lifestyle/x1558731033/Saving-the-people-killing-the-faith |title=Saving the people, killing the faith - News - Holland Sentinel - Holland, MI |publisher=Holland Sentinel |date=2009-08-08 |accessdate=2015-09-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306012853/http://www.hollandsentinel.com/lifestyle/x1558731033/Saving-the-people-killing-the-faith |archivedate=6 March 2012 }}</ref>

At the beginning of the 20th century, Iran had a total population of just below 10 million, with an approximate ethnic composition of:
6 million Persians (60%), 
2.5 million Azeris (25%), 
0.2 million Mazandaranis and Gilakis each (2% each).<ref>Ervand Abrahimian, "A History of Modern Iran", Cambridge University Press, 2008. Page 18: "Communal Composition of Iran, 1900 Persian 6 million Azeris 2.5 million Mazandaranis 200,000 Gilakis 200,000 Taleshis 20,000 Tatis 20,000"</ref>

==Iranian-speaking peoples==
{{further information|Iranian peoples|Persian peoples}}

===Persians===
{{Main article|Persian people}}

Iran used to be called [[Persia]] until 1935, by that definition all Iranians were considered '''Persian''' regardless of their ethnicity. The term "Persians" refers to an ethnic group who speak the Western dialect of [[Persian language|Persian]] and live in the modern country of Iran as well as the descendants of the people who emigrated from the territory of modern-day Iran to other countries.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}

{{citation needed span|Ethnic Persians inhabit traditionally the [[Tehran province]], [[Isfahan province]], [[Fars province]], [[Alborz province]], [[Razavi Khorasan]], [[South Khorasan]], [[Yazd province]], [[Kerman province]], [[Bushehr province]], [[Hormozgan province]], [[Markazi province]] (Arak), [[Qom province]], [[Semnan province]], [[Qazvin province]], the majority of [[Hamadan province]] including the city of Hamadan, majority of the [[North Khorasan]], majority of [[Khuzestan province]], northern half of [[Sistan and Baluchistan]] (Zabol), southern and western half of [[Golestan province]] including the provincial capital of Gorgan.|date=March 2013}}
The majority of the Iranian immigrants in the West and other parts of the world also hail from Persian speaking cities especially from [[Tehran]].{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}

According to the [[CIA World Factbook]], [[Persian people|Persians]] in Iran constitute up to 61% of the country's population.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2075.html |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref name="cia.gov">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203093100/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |archivedate=3 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>
Another source, [[Library of Congress]] <ref name="ReferenceB">See Iran in Encyclopedia of Islam, Leiden. C.E. Bosworth (editor)</ref> states Iran's [[Persian people|Persians]] compose 65% of the country's population.<ref name="LibraryOfCongress"/> However, other sources mention that Persians only comprise 50.5%,<ref name="terrorfreetomorrow1">{{cite web|url=http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |format=PDF |title=Terror Free Tomorrow: Ahmadinejad Front Runner in Upcoming Presidential Elections; |publisher=Terrorfreetomorrow.org |accessdate=2015-09-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723044939/http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> or 55.3%.<ref>[http://gulf2000.columbia.edu/images/maps/Iran_Languages_lg.jpg ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001091018/http://gulf2000.columbia.edu/images/maps/Iran_Languages_lg.jpg |date=1 October 2013 }}</ref> All these numbers include the [[Mazandarani people|Mazandaranis]] and [[Gilaki people|Gilakis]] as Persian people, though the CIA [[World Factbook]] makes a distinction between the Persian language and the [[Mazandarani language|Mazandarani]] and [[Gilaki language]], respectively.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="cia.gov"/>

===Kurds===
{{Main article|Kurds|Iranian Kurdistan}}

Iranian Kurds make up the majority of the population of Kordestan province, and, together with the Azeris, they are one of the two main ethnic groups in West Azerbaijan province.  In West Azerbaijan province, Kurds are concentrated in parts of the southern and western parts of the province.  The Feyli tribe of Kurds also make up a significant proportion of the populations of Kermanshah and Ilam provinces,{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} although Kermanshahi and Ilamian Kurds are Shia Muslims, in contrast to the mainstream Kurds, who are adherents of Sunni Islam. [[Kurmanji language|Kurmanji]]-speaking Kurds also form a plurality in North Khorasan province.

=== Mazandaranis ===

{{Main article|Mazanderani people}}

The [[Mazanderani people]] <ref>Area handbook for Iran, Harvey Henry Smith, American University (Washington, D.C.), Foreign Area Studies, page 89</ref> or [[Tabari people]] are an Iranian people whose homeland is the North of Iran (Tabaristan). Like the closely related [[Gilaks]], the [[Mazanderanis]] are a Caspian people who inhabit the south coast of the Caspian Sea, part of the historical region that used to be called [[Tabaristan]] and are currently one of the main ethnic groups residing in the northern parts of Iran. They speak the [[Mazandarani language]], a language native to around 4 million people, but all of them can speak Persian. The Alborz mountains mark the southern boundary of Mazanderani settlement.<ref>Dalb, Andrew (1998). Dictionary of Languages: The Definitive Reference to More Than 400 Languages. Columbia University Press. p. 226. {{ISBN|0-231-11568-7}}.</ref> The Mazanderani peoples number differs between three million and four million (2006 estimate) and many of them are farmers and fishermen.<ref>Middle East Patterns: Places, Peoples, and Politics By Colbert C. Held, John Cummings, Mildred McDonald Held,2005, page 119.</ref>

===Gilaks===
{{Main article|Gilaks}}

The [[Gilaki people]] or Gilaks are an Iranian people native to the northern Iran province of [[Gilan]] and are one of the main ethnic groups residing in the northern part of Iran. Gilaks, along with the closely related [[Mazandarani people]], comprise part of the Caspian people, who inhabit the southern and southwestern coastal regions of the [[Caspian Sea]]. They speak the [[Gilaki language]] and their population is estimated to be between 3 <ref>Colbert C. Held; John Cummings; Mildred McDonald Held (2005). Middle East Patterns: Places, Peoples, and Politics. p. 119</ref> to 4 <ref>"Iran Provinces". statoids.com.</ref> million (4% of the population). Gilaki people live both alongside the Alborz mountains, and in the surrounding plains. Consequentially, those living along the northern side of the Alborz mountains tend to raise livestock, while those living in the plains farm. Gilaks play an important role in provincial and national economy, supplying a large portion of the region's agricultural staples, such as rice, grains,<ref>M. ʿAṭāʾī, “Gozāreš-e eqteṣādī dar bāra-ye berenj-e Gīlān wa sāyer-e ḡallāt-e ān/Economic Report on Rice and Other Cereals in Gilan,” Taḥqīqāt-e eqteṣādī 2/5-6, 1342 Š., pp. 64-148 (Pers. ed.), 1963, pp. 32-53 (Eng. ed.)</ref> tobacco <ref>Idem, “La culture du tabac dans le Gilân,” Stud. Ir. 9/1, 1980, pp. 121-30.</ref> and tea.<ref>Ehlers, “Die Teelandschaft von Lahidjan/Nordiran,” in Beiträge zur Geographie der Tropen and Subtropen. Festschrift für Herbert Wilhelmy, Tübingen, 1970, pp. 229-42</ref> Other major industries include fishing and caviar exports, and the production of silk.<ref>[3] Bazin, Marcel. "GĪLĀN". Encyclopædia Iranica, X/VI, pp. 617-25. Retrieved 19 August 2014</ref>

===Lurs===
{{Main article|Lurs}}
'''Lur people''' speak the [[Lurish language|Luri]] language and inhabit parts of west – south western [[Iran]].<ref name="culturalsurvival1">{{cite web|url=http://www.culturalsurvival.org/publications/cultural-survival-quarterly/iran/lurs-iran |title=The Lurs of Iran |publisher=Cultural Survival |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Most Lur are Shi’a. They are the fourth largest [[ethnic group]] in Iran after the [[Persian people|Persians]], [[Azerbaijani people|Azeri]], and [[Kurds]].<ref name="terrorfreetomorrow1" /><ref name="CIA World Factbook Iran" /> They occupy [[Lorestan]], [[Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari Province|Chaharmahal and Bakhtiari]], [[Khuzestan Province|Khuzestan]], [[Isfahan Province|Isfahan]], [[Fars Province|Fars]], [[Bushehr Province|Bushehr]] and [[Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad Province|Kuh-Gilu-Boir Ahmed]] provinces.<ref name="culturalsurvival1"/> The authority of tribal elders remains a strong influence among the nomadic population. It is not as dominant among the settled urban population.  As is true in [[Bakhtiari people|Bakhtiari]] and Kurdish societies, Lur women have much greater freedom than women in other groups within the region.<ref>{{cite book|author=Edmonds, Cecil|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SzcyuAL7YOkC&pg=PA188|title=East and West of Zagros: Travel, War and Politics in Persia and Iraq 1913–1921|page=188|isbn=9789004173446|year=2010}}</ref> The Luri language is [[Indo-European migrations|Indo-European]]. The Lur people may be related to the Kurds from whom they "apparently began to be distinguished from... 1,000 years ago." The [[Sharafnama]] of [[Sharaf Khan Bidlisi]] "mentioned two Lur dynasties among the five Kurdish dynasties that had in the past enjoyed royalty or the highest form of sovereignty or independence."<ref>{{cite book|last=Gunter|first=Michael M.|title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|year=2011|edition=2nd|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0810867512|page=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zDRGO6EgapMC&pg=PA203}}</ref>  In the [[Mu'jam Al-Buldan]] of [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] mention is made of the Lurs as a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] tribe living in the mountains between [[Khuzestan]] and [[Isfahan]]. The term Kurd according to [[Richard Frye]] was used for all Iranian nomads (including the population of Luristan as well as tribes in Kuhistan and Baluchis in Kerman) for all nomads, whether they were linguistically connected to the Kurds or not.<ref>Richard Frye,"The Golden age of Persia", Phoneix Press, 1975. Second Impression December 2003. pp 111: "Tribes always have been a feature of Persian history, but the sources are extremely scant in reference to them since they did not 'make' history. The general designation 'Kurd' is found in many Arabic sources, as well as in Pahlavi book on the deeds of Ardashir the first Sassanian ruler, for all nomads no matter whether they were linguistically connected to the Kurds of today or not. The population of Luristan, for example, was considered to be Kurdish, as were tribes in Kuhistan and Baluchis in Kirman"</ref>

===Talysh===
{{Main article|Talysh people}}

The Talysh of Iran are about 430,000 and live mostly in the province of [[Gilan]] in north of Iran. They are indigenous to a region shared between [[Azerbaijan]] and Iran which spans the [[South Caucasus]] and the southwestern shore of the [[Caspian Sea]]. Another significant amount of Talysh live therefore also in the [[Republic of Azerbaijan]].<ref name="Looklex">{{cite web|author=Tore Kjeilen |url=http://i-cias.com/e.o/talysh_l.htm |title=Talysh - LookLex Encyclopaedia |publisher=I-cias.com |date=2008-08-19 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>

===Tats===
{{Main article|Tats of Iran}}

The [[Tats of Iran]] are centralised near the [[Alborz Mountains]], especially in the south of [[Qazvin province]].  
They speak the [[Tati language (Iran)|Tati language]], consisting of a group of [[northwestern Iranian languages|northwestern Iranian]] dialects closely related to the [[Talysh language]]. Persian and [[Azerbaijani language|Azeri]] are also spoken. 
Tats of Iran are mainly Shia Muslims and about 300,000 population.<ref>[[:fa:تات‌های ایران|Persian Wikipedia (تات‌های ایران)]]</ref>{{clarify|date=April 2012}}<ref>it is also spoken in some villages like Vafs and Chehreghan in the central areas of Iran like [[Gholamhossein Mosahab]]'s [[The Persian Encyclopedia]]</ref><ref>Paul, Ludwig (1998a). The position of Zazaki among West Iranian languages. In Proceedings of the 3rd European Conference of Iranian Studies, 11–15.09.1995, Cambridge, Nicholas Sims-Williams (ed.), 163–176. Wiesbaden: Reichert.</ref><ref>Andrew Dalby, Dictionary of Languages: the definitive reference to more than 400 languages, Columbia University Press, 2004, pg 496.</ref><ref name="Iranica">"Azari, the Old Iranian Language of Azerbaijan," Encyclopaedia Iranica, op. cit., Vol. III/2, 1987 by E. Yarshater</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/azerbaijan-vii |title=AZERBAIJAN vii. The Iranian Language of Azerb – Encyclopaedia Iranica |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopaediaislamica.com/madkhal2.php?sid=3003]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306083525/http://www.encyclopaediaislamica.com/madkhal2.php?sid=3003 |date=6 March 2012 }}</ref>

===Baloch===
The [[Balochi people|Baloch people]] of Iran live in southern and central parts of [[Sistan and Baluchistan|Sistan and Baluchestan]] province, one of the most remote and isolated areas of Iran, especially from the majority of the people. The northern part of the province is called Sistan and 63% of the population are ethnic Baloch while the rest are Persian Sistani. The Baloch are Sunni Muslims, in contrast to the Sistani Persians who are adherents of Shia Islam. The capital of [[Sistan and Baluchistan|Sistan and Baluchestan]] is [[Zahedan]] and is inhabited by Baloch people, the next largest city of the province is Zabol in Sistan and is inhabited predominantly by Persians. The town of [[Jask]] in neighbouring [[Hormozgan Province]] is also inhabited by Baloch people. They form one of the smallest ethnicities in Iran.

==Turkic==
{{further information|Turkic peoples}}
The largest Turkic group in Iran are the [[Iranian Azerbaijanis]], forming the second largest ethnicity in the nation after the majority Persian population.<ref name="books.google.nl"/>

Smaller Turkic groups account for about 2% of Iranian population between them,<ref name="CIA World Factbook Iran">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html#People |title=The World Factbook |publisher=Cia.gov |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview |title=TURKIC LANGUAGES OF PERSIA: AN OVERVIEW – Encyclopaedia Iranica |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> about half of this number is accounted for by the 
[[Iranian Turkmen]],{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} the other half comprises various tribal confederacies such as the [[Qashqai people|Qashqai]] or the [[Khorasani Turks]].

===Azerbaijanis===
{{Main article|Iranian Azerbaijanis}}

[[Iranian Azerbaijanis]] (also known as Iranian Turks) are a [[Turkic people|Turkic]]-[[Azerbaijani language|speaking]] people of mixed Caucasian, Iranian and Turkic origin,<ref>Minorsky, V.; Minorsky, V. "(Azerbaijan).'' Encyclopaedia of Islam. Edited by: P. Bearman, Th. Bianquis, C.E. Bosworth, E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill</ref> who live mainly in Iranian Azerbaijan. Estimated numbers or percentages vary significantly and many estimates cited appear to be politically motivated<ref>{{cite book|last1=Elling|first1=Rasmus Christian|title=Minorities in Iran: Nationalism and Ethnicity after Khomeini|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=978-1-349-29691-0|pages=17-18|url=http://www.palgrave.com/us/book/9780230115842}}</ref>. They are often considered the second largest ethnic group in Iran and the largest ethnic minority. The main estimations are stated below :
* 15%{{ref|Britannica|e}}<ref name="Britannica-Azerbaijani">{{cite news|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/46833/Azerbaijani|title= Azerbaijani|publisher=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |date=  |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>
* 15.5%{{ref|Ethnologue|f}}<ref name="Ethnologue-Azb">{{cite news|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/azb|title= Azerbaijani, South # A language of Iran|publisher=[[Ethnologue]] |year= 2013 |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>
* 16%{{ref|The World Factbook|a}}<ref name="CIA World Factbook">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |title=CIA World Factbook |first=CIA |last=CIA |accessdate=2012-05-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203093100/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html |archivedate=3 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name="Library of Congress">{{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Iran.pdf |title=Ethnic Groups and Languages of Iran |first=Library of Congress&nbsp;– Federal Research Division |last=Library of Congress|accessdate=2009-12-02}} 16% estimated in 2012</ref>{{ref|Iranica|g}}<ref name="Ali Gheissari" /><ref name="Ali Aldosari" /><ref name="Iranica-Iran">{{cite news|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/iran-v1-peoples-survey|title=IRAN v. PEOPLES OF IRAN (1) A General Survey |publisher=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] |date= March 29, 2012 |accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref><ref name="locprofile">{{cite web|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Iran.pdf|title=Country Profile: Iran|date=March 2006|accessdate=2008-04-21|author=Library of Congress, Federal Research Division|page=5}}</ref>
* 17%{{ref|Looklex Encyclopaedia|b}}<ref name="Looklex-Iran">{{cite news|url=http://looklex.com/e.o/iran.peoples.htm |title= Iran / Peoples|publisher= [[Looklex Encyclopaedia]]|date= |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>
* 21.6{{ref|New America Foundation|c}}<ref name="New America Foundation">{{cite news|url=http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |title=Results a new nationwide public opinion survey  of Iran |publisher=[[New America Foundation]] |date=June 12, 2009 |accessdate=13 August 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723044939/http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>
* 24-25 percent{{ref|Minority Rights|d}}<ref name="Minority Rights">{{cite news|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/?lid=5096|title=Azeris |publisher=[[Minority Rights Group International]] |year= 2009 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref>Rasmus Christian Elling, Minorities in Iran: Nationalism and Ethnicity after Khomeini,  Palgrave Macmillan, 2013. Excerpt: "The number of Azeris in Iran is heavily disputed. In 2005, Amanolahi estimated all Turkic-speaking communities in Iran to number no more than 9 million. CIA and Library of congress estimates range from 16 percent to 24 percent – that is, 12–18 million people if we employ the latest total figure for Iran's population (77.8 million). Azeri ethnicsts, on the other hand, argue that overall number is much higher, even as much as 50 percent or more of the total population. Such inflated estimates may have influenced some Western scholars who suggest that up to 30 percent (that is, some 23 million today) Iranians are Azeris."</ref><ref name="google1">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rWEbrv5oD8AC&pg=PT33&dq=argue+that+overall+number+is+much+higher,+even+as+much+as+50+percent+azeri&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WVJrUcnJE62g4AO5n4HADw&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA |title=Minorities in Iran: Nationalism and Ethnicity after Khomeini - Rasmus Christian Elling - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=2013-02-19 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>
*Minahan, James (2002). Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: S-Z. Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 1765. {{ISBN|978-0-313-32384-3}} "Approximately (2002e) 18,500,000 Southern Azeris in Iran, concentrated in the northwestern provinces of East and West Azerbaijan. It is difficult to determine the exact number of Southern Azeris in Iran, as official statistics are not published detailing Iran's ethnic structure. Estimates of the Southern Azeri population range from as low as 12 million up to 40% of the population of Iran – that is, nearly 27 million..."<ref name="google1"/><ref name="Criticism">
*Ali Gheissari, "Contemporary Iran:Economy, Society, Politics: Economy, Society, Politics", Oxford University Press, 2 April 2009. pg 300Azeri ethnonationalist activist, however, claim that number to be 24 million, hence as high as 35 percent of the Iranian population" 
*Rasmus Christian Elling, Minorities in Iran: Nationalism and Ethnicity after Khomeini,  Palgrave Macmillan, 2013. Excerpt: "The number of Azeris in Iran is heavily disputed. In 2005, Amanolahi estimated all Turkic-speaking communities in Iran to number no more than 9 million. CIA and Library of congress estimates range from 16 percent to 24 percent -- that is, 12-18 million people if we employ the latest total figure for Iran's population (77.8 million). Azeri ethnicsts, on the other hand, argue that overall number is much higher, even as much as 50 percent or more of the total population. Such inflated estimates may have influenced some Western scholars who suggest that up to 30 percent (that is, some 23 million today) Iranians are Azeris."</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |title=Iran |publisher=[[New America Foundation]] |date=June 12, 2009 |accessdate=31 August 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723044939/http://www.terrorfreetomorrow.org/upimagestft/TFT%20Iran%20Survey%20Report%200609.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>

In the Azerbaijan region, the population consists mainly of [[Azerbaijanis]].<ref name="Azerbaijan-Britannica">{{cite web |title=Azerbaijan |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica |date=2009-03-09 |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/46770/Azerbaijan}} (excerpt:"geographic region that comprises the extreme northwestern portion of Iran. It is bounded on the north by the Aras River, which separates it from independent Azerbaijan and Armenia; on the east by the Iranian region of Gīlān and the Caspian Sea; on the south by the Iranian regions of Zanjān and Kordestān; and on the west by Iraq and Turkey. Azerbaijan is 47,441 square miles (122,871 square km) in area.")</ref> Azeris form the largest ethnic group in Iranian Azerbaijan, while Kurds are the second largest group and a majority in many cities of [[West Azerbaijan Province]].<ref>Keith Stanley McLachlan, "The Boundaries of Modern Iran ", Published by UCL Press, 1994. pg 55</ref> Iranian Azerbaijan is one of the richest{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} and most densely populated regions of Iran. Many of these various linguistic, religious, and tribal minority groups, and Azeris themselves have settled widely outside the region.<ref>[[Encyclopaedia Iranica]], page 243 = accessed January 9, 2007</ref> The majority of Azeris are followers of [[Shi'a]] Islam. Iranian [[Azerbaijanis]] mainly reside in the northwest provinces, including the Iranian Azerbaijan provinces ([[East Azerbaijan Province|East Azerbaijan]], [[West Azerbaijan Province|West Azerbaijan]], [[Ardabil Province|Ardabil]], and [[Zanjan Province|Zanjan]]), as well as regions of the North<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Parviz Aḏkāʾi and EIr |first= | title= HAMADĀN i. GEOGRAPHY | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] | accessdate=2013-10-21|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/hamadan-i#}}</ref> to [[Hamadan County]]<ref name="Hamadan-Governor">{{cite news|url=http://hamedan-hm.ir/fa/showpages.aspx?mid=NDg=&spi=Mw==|title=زبانهاي رايج و نوع گويش در شهرستان |publisher=Governor of [[Hamadan]] |date= |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> and [[Shara District]]<ref name="Hamadan-Governor" /> in the East [[Hamadan Province]], and some regions of [[Qazvin Province]].<ref name="Country Study Guide-Azerbaijanis">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0KOSUrLPC6IC&pg=PA152&dq=majority+of+the+population+of+East+Azarbaijan+and+a+majority+of+West+Azarbaijan.#v=onepage&q=majority%20of%20the%20population%20of%20East%20Azarbaijan%20and%20a%20majority%20of%20West%20Azarbaijan.&f=false |title=Country Study Guide-Azerbaijanis |publisher=STRATEGIC INFORMATION AND DEVELOPMENTS-USA |date= |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref><ref name="Iran-Azerbaijanis">{{cite news|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+ir0052) |title=Iran-Azerbaijanis |publisher=[[Library of Congress Country Studies]] |date=December 1987 |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref> Some Azerbaijani minorities also live in [[Markazi Province|Markazi]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/moarefi|title=معرفی استان مرکزی |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance (Iran)|Office of Culture and Islamic Guidance]] |date= |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> [[Kordestan Province|Kordestan]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/322153/Kordestan|title=Kordestān |publisher=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |date= |accessdate=21 October 2013}}</ref> [[Gilan Province|Gilan]]<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Bazin |first=Marcel| title= GĪLĀN i. GEOGRAPHY AND ETHNOGRAPHY | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] | accessdate=16 October 2013|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gilan-i-geography}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Parviz Aḏkāʾi and EIr |first=| title= GILĀN xiv. Ethnic Groups | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] | accessdate=16 October 2013|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gilan-xiv-ethnic-groups}}</ref> and [[Kermanshah Province|Kermanshah]] provinces.{{ref|Songor|h}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Michael Knüppel |first=E. | title= Turkic languages of persia | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] | accessdate=2013-09-19|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview}}</ref> Azerbaijanis also make up significant minorities in various parts of central Iran, especially [[Tehran]],<ref name="R. Tapper">{{cite news|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/azerbaijan-vi |title=AZERBAIJAN vi. Population and its Occupations and Culture |publisher= [[Encyclopædia Iranica]]|date= August 18, 2011|accessdate= August 18, 2012}}</ref> where they constitute around 25%<ref name="Tehran">{{cite web|url=http://looklex.com/e.o/teheran.htm |title=Tehran |publisher=[[Looklex Encyclopaedia]] |date= |accessdate=2013-07-04}}</ref> to one-third of the population.<ref name="Country Study Guide-Azerbaijanis"/><ref name="Iran-Azerbaijanis"/><ref>National Bibliography Number: 2887741 / plan review and assess the country's culture indicators (indicators Ghyrsbty) {report}: [[Tehran Province]] / General Council of the Order of the Executive Director is responsible for planning and policy: Mansoor Vaezi; run company experienced researchers Us - {{ISBN|978-600-6627-42-7}} * Publication Status: Tehran - Institute Press book, published in 1391 * appearance: 296 p: table (the color), diagrams (colored part)</ref>

=== Turkmen ===
{{main article|Iranian Turkmen}}
[[Iranian Turkmen]] are primarily concentrated in the [[Provinces of Iran|provinces]] of [[Golestān Province|Golestān]] and [[North Khorasan Province|North Khorasan]]. The largest Turkmen city in Iran is [[Gonbad-e Qabus (city)|Gonbad-e Kavoos]], followed by [[Bandar Torkaman]]. Iranian Turkmen are mostly Sunni Muslims.

===Turkic tribal groups===
{{Main article|Qashqai people|Khorasani Turks|Afshar people|Qarai Turks}}
The [[Qashqai people]] mainly live in the provinces of [[Fars Province|Fars]], [[Khuzestan]] and southern [[Isfahan province|Isfahan]], especially around the city of [[Shiraz]] in Fars. They speak the [[Qashqai language]] which is a member of the [[Turkic languages|Turkic family of languages]]. The Qashqai were originally [[nomadic people|nomadic]] [[pastoralism|pastoralists]] and some remain so today. 
The traditional nomadic Qashqai travelled with their flocks each year from the summer highland pastures north of Shiraz roughly 480&nbsp;km or 300&nbsp;mi south to the winter pastures on lower (and warmer) lands near the [[Persian Gulf]], to the southwest of Shiraz. The majority, however, have now become partially or wholly sedentary. The trend towards settlement has been increasing markedly since the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/qasqai-tribal-confederacy-i |title=QAŠQĀʾI TRIBAL CONFEDERACY i. HISTORY – Encyclopaedia Iranica |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>

The [[Khorasani Turks]] are [[Turkic languages|Turkic]]-speaking people inhabiting parts of north-eastern [[Iran]], and in the neighbouring regions of [[Turkmenistan]] up to beyond the [[Amu Darya River]]. They speak the [[Khorasani Turkic language|Khorasani Turkic]] and live in [[North Khorasan Province|North Khorasan]], [[Razavi Khorasan Province|Razavi Khorasan,]] and [[Golestan Province|Golestan]] provinces alongside Turkmens.

==Semitic==

=== Arabs===
{{Main article|Iranian Arabs}}
2% of Iran's citizens are Arabs.<ref name="cia.gov"/> {{citation needed span|text=A 1998 report by [[UNCHR]] reported 1 million of them live in border cities of [[Khuzestan Province]], they are believed to constitute 20% to 25% of the population in the province, most of whom being Shi'a. In [[Khuzestan]], Arabs are a minority in the province. They are the dominant ethnic group in [[Shadegan]], [[Hoveyzeh]] and [[Susangerd]], a significant group in the rural areas of [[Abadan]] (The city of Abadan is inhabited by Iranians who speak the Abadani dialect of Persian as well as Arabs), and together with Persians, Arabs are one of the two main ethnic groups in [[Ahvaz]]. Most other cities in Khuzestan province are either inhabited by the Lur, Bakhtiari or Persian ethnic groups.|date=November 2016}} The historically large and oil-rich cities of Mahshahr, Behbahan, Masjed Soleyman, Izeh, Dezful, Shushtar, Andimeshk, Shush, Ramhormoz, Baghemalak, Gotvand, Lali, Omidieh, Aghajari, Hendijan, Ramshir, Haftkel, Bavi are inhabited by people who speak either Luri, Bakhtiari and Persian languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/iran_081205.doc |accessdate=25 August 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090718101816/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/iran_081205.doc |archivedate=18 July 2009 }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2016}} There are smaller communities in [[Qom Province|Qom]] where there are a significant number of Arabs being of [[Lebanese people in Iran|Lebanese]] descent, as well as [[Razavi Khorasan]] and [[Fars Province|Fars]] provinces. Iranian Arab communities are also found in [[Bahrain]], [[Iraq]], [[Lebanon]], [[Kuwait]], [[United Arab Emirates]], and [[Qatar]].

=== Assyrians===
{{Main article|Assyrians in Iran}}

The [[Assyrian people]] of Iran are a [[Semitic people]] who speak [[Assyrian Neo-Aramaic|modern Assyrian]], a [[neo-Aramaic language]] descended from [[Syriac language|Classical Syriac]], and are [[Eastern Christianity|Eastern Rite Christians]] belonging mostly to the [[Assyrian Church of the East]] and, to a lesser extent, to the [[Chaldean Catholic Church]], [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and [[Ancient Church of the East]].{{sfnp|Hooglund|2008|pp=100–101}} They claim descent from the ancient peoples of [[Mesopotamis]]. They share a common identity, rooted in shared linguistic and religious traditions, with [[Assyrians in Iraq]] and elsewhere in the Middle East such as [[Syria]] and [[Turkey]], as well as with the [[Assyrian–Chaldean–Syriac diaspora|Assyrian diaspora]].{{sfnp|Hooglund|2008|pp=100–101}}

The Assyrian community in Iran numbered approximately 200,000 prior to the [[Islamic Revolution]] of 1979. However, after the revolution many Assyrians left the country, primarily for the United States, and the 1996 census counted only 32,000 Assyrians.{{sfnp|Hooglund|2008|pp=100–101, 295}}  Current estimates of the Assyrian population in Iran range from 32,000 ({{as of|2005|lc=on}}){{sfnp|Hooglund|2008|p=295}} to 50,000 ({{as of|2007|lc=on}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aina.org/brief.html |title=Brief History of Assyrians |last=BetBasoo |first=Peter |date=1 April 2007 |website=[[Assyrian International News Agency]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KKWk56jd?url=http://www.aina.org/brief.html |archivedate=13 October 2013 |accessdate=12 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>  The Iranian capital, [[Tehran]], is home to the majority of Iranian Assyrians; however, approximately 15,000 Assyrians reside in northern Iran, in [[Urmia]] and various Assyrian villages in the surrounding area.{{sfnp|Hooglund|2008|pp=100–101}}

===Jews===
{{Main article|Persian Jews}}

Judaism is one of the oldest religions practiced in Iran and dates back to late biblical times. The biblical books of Isaiah, Daniel, Ezra, Nehemiah, Chronicles, and Esther contain references to the life and experiences of Jews in Iran.

By various estimates, 10,800 Jews<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/jewpop.html |title=Jewish Population of the World |publisher=Jewish Virtual Library |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> remain in Iran, mostly in Tehran, Isfahan, and Shiraz. BBC reported Yazd is home to ten Jewish families, six of them related by marriage, however some{{Who|date=November 2016}} estimate the number is much higher. Historically, Jews maintained a presence in many more Iranian cities. Iran contains the largest Jewish population of any Muslim country except Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sephardicstudies.org/iran.html |title=IRAN: Life of Jews Living in Iran |publisher=Sephardicstudies.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>

A number of groups of Jews of Iran have split off since ancient times. They are now recognized as separate communities, such as the Bukharan Jews and Mountain Jews. In addition, there are several thousand in Iran who are, or who are the direct descendants of, Jews who have converted to Islam and the Bahá'í Faith.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bahai-library.com/maneck_conversion_minorities_iran |title=Conversion of Religious Minorities to the Bahá'í Faith in Iran |publisher=Bahai-library.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>

===Mandaeans===
{{Main article|Mandeans|Mandaeans#Iranian_Mandaeans}}
Iranian [[Mandaeans]] live mainly in the [[Khuzestan Province]] in southern Iran.<ref>صابئین ایران‌زمین، عکس: عباس تحویلدار، متن: مسعود فروزنده، آلن برونه، تهران: نشر کلید: ۱۳۷۹، شابک: 9789649064550، ص۸</ref> Mandeans are a [[Mandaic language|Mandaic]] speaking [[Semitic race|Semitic people]] who follow their own distinctive [[Gnostic]] religion [[Mandaeism]], venerating [[John the Baptist]] as the true Messiah. Like the [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] of Iran, their origins lie in ancient [[Mesopotamia]]. They number some 10,000 people in Iran,<ref>Contrera, Russell. "Saving the people, killing the faith – Holland, MI". The Holland Sentinel. Retrieved 2011-12-17.</ref> though Alarabiya has put their number as high as 60,000 in 2011.<ref name=alarabiya0612>{{cite web|author=<!--[if IE 6]> <![endif]--> |url=http://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2011/12/06/181123.html |title=Iran Mandaeans in exile following persecution |publisher=Alarabiya.net |date=2011-12-06 |accessdate=2011-12-17}}</ref>

==Caucasus-derived groups==
{{main article|Peoples of the Caucasus in Iran}}

===Armenians===
{{Main article|Iranian Armenians}}

The current Iranian-Armenian population is somewhere around 500,000.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite web|url=http://lexicorient.com/e.o/iran_4.htm |title=Religions\publisher=Lexicorient.com |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> They mostly live in [[Tehran]] and [[Jolfa district]]. After the [[Iranian Revolution]], many Armenians immigrated to [[Armenian diaspora|Armenian diasporic]] communities in [[North America]] and [[western Europe]]. Today the Armenians are Iran's largest [[Christians in Iran|Christian]] religious minority, followed by Assyrians.

===Georgians===
{{Main article| Iranian Georgians}}
Iranian Georgians are [[Twelver Shia]] Muslims, whereas the vast majority of Georgians elsewhere in the world are [[Christian]].

The [[Georgian language]] is the only [[Caucasian languages|Caucasian language]] fully functioning in Iran and it's spoken only by those that live in [[Fereydan]] and [[Fereydunshahr]], and in smaller pockets all over Iran. Almost all other communities of [[Iranian Georgians]] in Iran have already lost their language, but retain a clear Georgian identity.

Once a very large minority in Iran mainly due to mass deportations by the various early modern age and modern age Iranian empires ([[Safavids]], [[Afsharids]], and [[Qajar dynasty|Qajars]]), of their Georgian subjects, nowadays, due to intermarrying and assimilating the number of Georgians in Iran is estimated to be over 100,000. However, the amount of Iranians with partial or assimilated Georgian ancestry is estimated to exceed millions.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}

The [[Georgian language]] is still used by many of the Georgians in [[Iran]]. The centre of [[Georgian people|Georgians]] in Iran is [[Fereydunshahr]], a small city 150&nbsp;km to the west of [[Isfahan (city)|Isfahan]]. The western part of Isfahan province is historically called [[Fereydan]]. In this area there are 10 Georgian towns and villages around [[Fereydunshahr]]. In this region the old Georgian identity is retained the best compared to other places in Iran. In many major Iranian cities, such as [[Tehran]], [[Isfahan]], [[Karaj]] and [[Shiraz]], and [[Rasht]] live Georgians too.

In many other places such as [[Najafabad]], [[Rahmatabad, Najafabad|Rahmatabad]], Yazdanshahr and Amir Abad (near Isfahan) there are also Georgian pockets and villages. In [[Mazandaran Province]] in northern Iran, there are ethnic Georgians too. They live in the town of [[Behshahr]], and also in Behshahr county, in Farah Abad, and many other places, which are usually called "Gorji Mahalle" (Georgian Neighbourhood). Most of these Georgians no longer speak the [[Georgian language]], but retain aspects of [[Georgian culture]] and a Georgian identity. Some{{Who|date=November 2016}} argue that Iranian Georgians retain remnants of Christian traditions, but there is no evidence for this.

===Circassians===
{{main article|Circassians in Iran}}
Like with the Georgians, once a very large minority in Iran all the way from the [[Safavid Dynasty|Safavid]] to the [[Qajar Dynasty|Qajar]] era, the vast majority of the [[Circassians]] have been assimilated into the population nowadays. However, significant numbers remain present,<ref name="FdyRswC p 141">[https://books.google.com/books?id=stl97FdyRswC&pg=PA141&lpg=PA141&dq=number+of+circassians+in+iran&source=bl&ots=u_SmExfuC8&sig=2lK8k9IsUQZyjCtdKqIAIr6Rc5M&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBDgKahUKEwins7Whz4vGAhVRCNsKHb9pAME#v=onepage&q=number%20of%20circassians%20in%20iran&f=false ''Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Africa and the Middle East''] Facts On File, Incorporated {{ISBN|143812676X}} p. 141</ref> and they are the second-largest Caucasian ethnic group in the nation after the Georgians.<ref name="FdyRswC p 141"/>

From [[Jean Chardin|Sir John Chardin's]] "Travels in Persia, 1673–1677":

''There is scarce a Gentleman in Persia, whose Mother is not a Georgian, or a Circassian Woman; to begin with the King, who commonly is a Georgian, or a Circassian by the Mother's side.''

[[Circassians]] alongside the Georgians were deported en masse by the Shah's to fulfil roles in the civil administration, the military, and the royal Harem, but also as craftsmen, farmers, amongst other professions.<ref>P Bushkovitch, ''Princes Cherkasskii or Circassian Murzas'', pp.12–13</ref><ref name="ČARKAS">{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/carkas-cherkes-term-used-in-persian-arabic-and-turkic-for-the-circassian-people-of-the-northwest-caucasus-who-call-thems |title=ČARKAS |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |accessdate=28 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SYOXY2Np?url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/carkas-cherkes-term-used-in-persian-arabic-and-turkic-for-the-circassian-people-of-the-northwest-caucasus-who-call-thems |archivedate=13 September 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>
Circassian women were both in [[Ottoman Turkey]] and Persia desired for [[Circassian beauties|their beauty]], while the men were known as fearsome warriors.
Notable Iranians of Circassian descent of the past include [[Teresia Sampsonia]], [[Shah Abbas II]], [[Suleiman I of Persia|Shah Suleiman I]], [[Pari Khan Khanum]] (daughter of [[Shah Tahmasp]], involved in many court intrigues), [[Shamkhal Sultan]], Jamshid Beg (the assassinator of [[Ismail II|Shah Ismail II]]), and [[Anna Khanum]].
Traces of Circassian settlements have lasted into the 20th century,<ref name="ČARKAS"/> and small pockets still exist scattered over the country, even after centuries of absorbing and assimilating,<ref name="Carl Waldman pp.175"/><ref name="mcha.kbsu.ru">{{cite web|url=http://mcha.kbsu.ru/english/m_hist_01E.htm.html|title=International Circassian Association|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> such as in [[Fars Province|Fars]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/carkas-cherkes-term-used-in-persian-arabic-and-turkic-for-the-circassian-people-of-the-northwest-caucasus-who-call-thems |title=ČARKAS |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |accessdate=26 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SYOXY2Np?url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/carkas-cherkes-term-used-in-persian-arabic-and-turkic-for-the-circassian-people-of-the-northwest-caucasus-who-call-thems |archivedate=13 September 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Rasht]], [[Asupas|Aspas]], [[Gilan Province|Gilan]], [[Mazandaran]], and the capital [[Tehran]] (due to contemporary internal migration). Their total number nowadays is unknown due to heavy assimilation and lack of censuses based on ethnicity, but are known to be significant.<ref name="FdyRswC p 141"/><ref name="mcha.kbsu.ru"/><ref>Pierre, Oberling ''Georgians and Circassians in Iran''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/iran-vii6-in-islamic-iran-language-families|title=IRAN vii. NON-IRANIAN LANGUAGES (6) in Islamic Iran|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> Due to the same assimilation however, no sizeable number speaks the [[Circassian language]] anymore.<ref name="mcha.kbsu.ru"/>

==Recent immigration==
{{anchor|Immigration}}
Most of the large [[Circassians|Circassian]] migrational waves towards mainland Iran stem from the Safavid and Qajar era, however a certain amount also stem from the relatively recent arrivals that migrated as the Circassians [[Ethnic cleansing of Circassians|were displaced from the Caucasus]] in the 19th century. A [[Afro-Iranian|Black African]] population exists due to [[Slavery in Iran|historical slavery]].
A substantial number of [[Russians in Iran|Russians]] arrived in the early 20th century as refugees from the [[Russian revolution]], but their number has dwindled following the [[Iran crisis of 1946]] and the [[Iranian Revolution]].
In the 20th to 21st centuries, there has been limited immigration to Iran from [[Turkish people in Iran|Turkey]], [[Iraqis in Iran|Iraqis]] (especially huge numbers during the 1970s known as [[Moaved]]s), [[Afghans in Iran|Afghanistan]] (mostly arriving as refugees in 1978), [[Lebanese people in Iran|Lebanese]] (especially in [[Qom province|Qom]], though a Lebanese community has been present in the nation for centuries),
[[Indians in Iran|Indians]] (mostly arriving temporarily during the 1950s to 1970s, typically working as doctors, engineers, and teachers), [[Koreans in Iran|Koreans]] (mostly in the 1970s as labour migrants), [[Chinese people in Iran|China]] (mostly since the 2000s working in engineering or business projects), and [[Pakistanis in Iran|Pakistan]], partly due to labour migrants and partly to [[Baloch people|Balochi]] ties across the Iranian-Pakistani border. 
About 200,000 [[Iraqis in Iran|Iraqis]] arrived as refugees in 2003,{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}} mostly living in refugee camps near the border; an unknown number of these has since returned to Iraq.

Over the same period, there has also been substantial emigration from Iran, especially since the [[Iranian revolution]] (see [[Iranian diaspora]], [[Human capital flight from Iran]], [[Jewish exodus from Iran]]), especially
to the [[Iranian American|United States]], [[Iranian Canadian|Canada]], [[Iranians in Germany|Germany]], [[Iranian Jews in Israel|Israel]], and [[Swedish Iranians|Sweden]].

